What is Composite Metal Foam (CMF) and Why is Demand Increasing?
Composite Metal Foam (CMF) is an advanced cellular metallic material composed of hollow metallic spheres typically manufactured from carbon steel, stainless steel, titanium, or other alloys embedded within a solid metallic matrix such as steel, aluminum, or other engineering metals. This unique architecture creates a material that combines exceptional mechanical strength with significantly lower weight compared to conventional solid metals.

Unlike traditional structural metals, Composite Metal Foam delivers superior energy absorption, thermal insulation, acoustic damping, fire resistance, vibration control, and radiation shielding. These properties make CMF particularly valuable in demanding environments including aerospace structures, military armor, electric vehicle battery enclosures, industrial equipment, petrochemical facilities, and advanced construction projects. Continuous advancements in powder metallurgy, additive manufacturing, and metal infiltration technologies are further enhancing CMF performance while improving manufacturing efficiency.

